                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p>A block of compact limestone (colour not reported), described as 'pietra di Taormina'. Intact above, to right and below (although with some chipping to the edges, and with the upper right corner of the face lost; broken approximately in half (?) on the left side. The measurements reported by Orsi (W 29, H 32, D 26) differ slightly from those reported by Cavallari and repeated by Manganaro.</p>
                                    <material ana="#material.stone.limestone" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/66.html">limestone</material>
                                    <objectType ana="#object.block" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/189.html">block</objectType>
                                    <dimensions><!--Cavallari-->
                                        <height unit="cm">28</height>
                                        <width unit="cm">31</width>
                                        <depth unit="cm">23</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition ana="#condition.damaged"/>
		    </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><p>Four lines of Greek letters; the text appears to be centred on the stone, with slight vacat below.</p>
                                    <rs ana="#execution.chiselled" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1">chiselled</rs>
                                	<damage ana="#text_condition.incomplete"/>
			</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><p>. Based upon the single published photograph: regularly and neatly carved fine lettters without serfis or significant terminations. Alpha has straight bar; Mu has vertical first and last, with midstrokes descending halfway; omicron is small and mid-line; sigma has diverging top and bottom strokes, the mid-strokes meeting at half width; omega is nearly full height, slightly ovoid, open with short horizontal tails. No editor records the size of the letters.</p>
                                <locus from="line1" to="line1">Line 1</locus>
                                <dimensions type="letterHeight">
                                    <height unit="mm"/>
                                </dimensions>
                                <locus from="line1" to="line2">Interlineation line 1 to 2</locus>
                                <dimensions type="interlinear">
                                    <height unit="mm"/>
                                </dimensions>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
